TY  - JOUR
T1  - Line Balancing-Sequencing for Mixed-Model Assembly
AU  - Thomopoulos, Nick T.
Y1  - 1967/10/01
PY  - 1967
DA  - 1967/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.14.2.B59
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.14.2.B59
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - B-59
EP  - B-75
VL  - 14
IS  - 2
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Mixed-model assembly occurs when more than one model of the same general product are intermixed on one assembly line. The amount of work required to assemble units can vary from model to model, creating an uneven flow of work along the line. This paper describes a procedure of adapting single-model line balancing techniques to mixed-model schedules. The paper also introduces a sequencing procedure for determining the order in which models are to flow down the line. Because the line balancing and sequencing procedures consider a wide variety of factors, they are applicable to many types of assembly lines.
AB  - Mixed-model assembly occurs when more than one model of the same general product are intermixed on one assembly line. The amount of work required to assemble units can vary from model to model, creating an uneven flow of work along the line. This paper describes a procedure of adapting single-model line balancing techniques to mixed-model schedules. The paper also introduces a sequencing procedure for determining the order in which models are to flow down the line. Because the line balancing and sequencing procedures consider a wide variety of factors, they are applicable to many types of assembly lines.
